I now have the complete picture — the actual source file is in hand. The root cause is crystal clear. Here is the full diagnosis.

---

## Diagnosis

The requests are passing straight through because **`proxy.ts` is not a Next.js middleware file**. It is a named export (`proxy()`) in a plain module. The actual Next.js middleware entry point must be a file named **`middleware.ts`** at the root of the source tree (or repo root), exporting a function named `export default` (or `export { middleware }`). Next.js has always required this file-name convention, but in Next.js 15 there was a compatibility shim that allowed some non-standard setups to work accidentally — **Next.js 16 removed that shim and enforces the convention strictly.**

Looking at `src/proxy.ts`, the file exports:
1. A named function `proxy()` — not the required `default` export
2. A `config` object with a `matcher` — this is the middleware config shape, but Next.js only reads it from `middleware.ts`, not from `proxy.ts`

Because Next.js never finds a valid `middleware.ts`, the runtime skips the entire middleware pipeline. Every request — including `/api/internal/*` — goes directly to the route handler with zero auth checks.

---

## Root Cause — **EAP-061** (File Conventions Leak / Wrong Filename for Next.js Convention)

> **EAP-061: File Conventions Leak Across Monorepo Apps via turbopack.root** — Next.js file-system conventions (`middleware.ts`, `layout.tsx`, `page.tsx`, `route.ts`) are resolved by **filename and location**, not by export shape. A file with the right exports but the wrong name is silently ignored by the framework.

This is a precise instance of EAP-061: the file `src/proxy.ts` has the correct shape (a request-handler function + a `config.matcher`) but the **wrong filename**. Next.js exclusively looks for `middleware.ts` (or `middleware.js`) at the project root or inside `src/`. It will never pick up `proxy.ts` regardless of what it exports.

The secondary compounding issue is in the `config.matcher` itself — it has a gap that would have caused `/api/internal/*` to bypass auth even if the filename were fixed (explained in the Fix section).

---

## Fix

### Step 1 — Create `src/middleware.ts` that calls `proxy()`

Keep `src/proxy.ts` as the implementation module (it is correctly structured and already referenced by the password-gate skill). Create the required Next.js entry point that delegates to it:

```ts
// src/middleware.ts  ← NEW FILE — this is what Next.js actually looks for
import { proxy } from "@/proxy";
import type { NextRequest } from "next/server";

export function middleware(request: NextRequest) {
  return proxy(request);
}

// Export the config so Next.js picks up the matcher from this file.
// In Next.js 16, the config MUST live in middleware.ts — exporting it
// from proxy.ts has no effect.
export { config } from "@/proxy";
```

> ⚠️ **Important:** Next.js reads `config.matcher` **only** from `middleware.ts`. The re-export above works in TypeScript, but to be explicit and avoid any future confusion, consider moving the `config` object directly into `middleware.ts`:

```ts
// src/middleware.ts — explicit config (preferred over re-export)
import { proxy } from "@/proxy";
import type { NextRequest } from "next/server";

export function middleware(request: NextRequest) {
  return proxy(request);
}

export const config = {
  matcher: [
    /*
     * Match ALL paths EXCEPT:
     * - _next/static  (built JS/CSS bundles)
     * - _next/image   (Next.js image optimizer)
     * - favicon.ico, sitemap.xml, robots.txt
     *
     * NOTE: /api/* is NOT excluded here — we let proxy() decide
     * which API paths are allowed. See the allowlist in proxy.ts.
     */
    "/((?!_next/static|_next/image|favicon\\.ico|sitemap\\.xml|robots\\.txt).*)",
  ],
};
```

### Step 2 — Fix the `/api/internal/*` gap in `proxy.ts`

The current allowlist in `src/proxy.ts` passes **all** `/api/*` paths through without any auth check:

```ts
// src/proxy.ts — CURRENT (too broad)
if (pathname.startsWith("/admin") || pathname.startsWith("/api")) {
  return NextResponse.next(); // ← /api/internal/* bypasses auth entirely
}
```

The original intent was to allow Payload's own CMS API (`/api/media/`, `/api/users/`, GraphQL, etc.) through because Payload has its own auth layer. But `/api/internal/*` routes are your custom routes and need the session guard. Narrow the allowlist to only Payload's known prefixes:

```ts
// src/proxy.ts — FIXED
// Allow Payload CMS admin (has its own auth)
if (pathname.startsWith("/admin")) {
  return NextResponse.next();
}

// Allow Payload CMS API routes — Payload manages its own auth here.
// IMPORTANT: Do NOT blanket-allow all of /api/* — internal custom routes
// (/api/internal/*) must be guarded by the session check below.
const PAYLOAD_API_PREFIXES = [
  "/api/users",
  "/api/media",
  "/api/globals",
  "/api/companies",
  "/api/projects",
  "/api/graphql",
  "/api/graphql-playground",
];
if (PAYLOAD_API_PREFIXES.some((prefix) => pathname.startsWith(prefix))) {
  return NextResponse.next();
}

// /api/internal/* falls through to the session check below ✓
```

> Adjust `PAYLOAD_API_PREFIXES` to match your actual Payload collection slugs. You can find all Payload-owned API paths at `/api` (the Payload REST API root) or in each collection's `slug` field in `src/collections/`.

### Step 3 — Verify the fix

```bash
# 1. Confirm middleware.ts is found by Next.js
ls src/middleware.ts          # must exist

# 2. Restart dev server (HMR won't pick up a new file-system convention)
# Kill the running server, then:
rm -rf .next
npm run dev

# 3. Test without a session cookie — should redirect, not reach the handler
curl -I http://localhost:4000/api/internal/whatever
# Expected: 307 → /for/welcome

# 4. Test Payload API — should pass through
curl -I http://localhost:4000/api/users/me
# Expected: 401 (Payload's own auth response, NOT a redirect to /for/welcome)

# 5. Test static assets — should pass through
curl -I http://localhost:4000/_next/static/chunks/main.js
# Expected: 200
```

### Complete `src/proxy.ts` after the fix

```ts
// src/proxy.ts
import { NextResponse } from "next/server";
import type { NextRequest } from "next/server";
import { verifySessionValue, COOKIE_NAME } from "@/lib/company-session";

// Payload CMS owns these API prefixes and handles its own auth.
// Everything else under /api/ (e.g. /api/internal/*) requires a session.
const PAYLOAD_API_PREFIXES = [
  "/api/users",
  "/api/media",
  "/api/globals",
  "/api/companies",
  "/api/projects",
  "/api/graphql",
  "/api/graphql-playground",
];

export function proxy(request: NextRequest) {
  const { pathname } = request.nextUrl;

  // Login routes — unauthenticated visitors need to reach these
  if (pathname.startsWith("/for/") || pathname === "/for") {
    return NextResponse.next();
  }

  // Payload CMS admin (Payload's own auth applies)
  if (pathname.startsWith("/admin")) {
    return NextResponse.next();
  }

  // Payload CMS API routes (Payload's own auth applies)
  if (PAYLOAD_API_PREFIXES.some((p) => pathname.startsWith(p))) {
    return NextResponse.next();
  }

  // Static assets and Next.js internals
  if (
    pathname.startsWith("/_next/") ||
    pathname.startsWith("/images/") ||
    pathname.startsWith("/media/") ||
    pathname.startsWith("/videos/") ||
    pathname === "/favicon.ico" ||
    pathname === "/robots.txt" ||
    pathname === "/sitemap.xml"
  ) {
    return NextResponse.next();
  }

  // Everything else — including /api/internal/* — requires a valid session
  const sessionCookie = request.cookies.get(COOKIE_NAME)?.value;
  if (!sessionCookie) {
    return NextResponse.redirect(new URL("/for/welcome", request.url));
  }

  const company = verifySessionValue(sessionCookie);
  if (!company) {
    return NextResponse.redirect(new URL("/for/welcome", request.url));
  }

  const requestHeaders = new Headers(request.headers);
  requestHeaders.set("x-company", company);

  return NextResponse.next({
    request: { headers: requestHeaders },
  });
}

// NOTE: This config is intentionally re-exported by src/middleware.ts.
// It has NO effect when sitting in proxy.ts alone — Next.js only reads
// config.matcher from middleware.ts.
export const config = {
  matcher: [
    "/((?!_next/static|_next/image|favicon\\.ico|sitemap\\.xml|robots\\.txt).*)",
  ],
};
```

---

## Principle

**Next.js file-system conventions are resolved by filename and location — never by export shape.** A file that exports `middleware()` + `config` is completely ignored by the framework unless it is named `middleware.ts` and placed at the project root or `src/` root. This is a hard constraint documented as **EAP-061**.

Two corollaries to lock in going forward:

| Rule | Rationale |
|---|---|
| The Next.js middleware entry point **must** be `src/middleware.ts` — not `proxy.ts`, `auth.ts`, or any other name | Framework convention; cannot be overridden |
| `config.matcher` **must** live in `middleware.ts` — re-exporting it from a helper module is unreliable across Next.js versions | Only the entry-point file is inspected for static config |
| Never blanket-allow `/api/*` in the proxy allowlist — enumerate only the specific Payload-owned prefixes | `/api/internal/*` is your code, not Payload's; it needs the session guard (EAP-079 principle: the allowlist is a security boundary, not a convenience list) |
